ons closely.\", \"rainfall_forecast\": \"Precipitation: 0.0 mm, Data unavailable\", \"spraying_advisory\": \"It is relatively safe to spray pesticides/fungicides today, given the low wind speed and no forecasted rainfall, but always follow recommended safety guidelines.\", \"current_temperature\": \"25.0°C\", \"weather_recommendations\": [\"Recommendation 1: Implement efficient irrigation systems to minimize water loss.\", \"Recommendation 2: Consider using windbreaks to protect plants from potential wind damage.\"]}}','[{\"content\": \"Integrated Pest Management (IPM) principles: 1. Cultural control: Crop rotation, resistant varieties, sanitation. 2. Biological control: Predatory insects, Bt, Trichoderma. 3. Chemical control: Last resort, use registered pesticides at correct dosage. 4. Monitoring: Regular scouting every 5–7 days.\", \"metadata\": {\"type\": \"ipm\", \"source\": \"fao.org\"}, \"relevance\": 1.4639}, {\"content\": \"Tomato cultivation requires well-drained loamy soil with pH 6.0–7.0. Scientific name: Solanum lycopersicum. Growth duration: 60–90 days after transplanting. NPK recommendation: 120:60:60 kg/ha. Requires staking for indeterminate varieties.\", \"metadata\": {\"crop\": \"Tomato\", \"type\": \"overview\", \"source\": \"icar.org.in\"}, \"relevance\": 1.6131}, {\"content\": \"Powdery Mildew affects many crops including wheat, grapes, and cucurbits. White powdery coating appears on leaves and stems. Management: Apply sulfur-based fungicides. Improve air circulation. Avoid excess nitrogen fertilization.\", \"metadata\": {\"crop\": \"Wheat\", \"source\": \"usda.gov\", \"disease\": \"Powdery Mildew\"}, \"relevance\": 1.6473}, {\"content\": \"General crop storage principles: Temperature and humidity control are critical. Most vegetables: 0–10°C, 85–95% RH. Grains: <15°C, <14% moisture. Fruits: 10–15°C, 85–90% RH. Use hermetic bags or cold rooms to extend shelf life.\", \"metadata\": {\"type\": \"storage\", \"source\": \"fao.org\"}, \"relevance\": 1.6801}]',28.6139,77.209,16.5,'completed','','2026-06-11 08:42:15.167650','2026-06-11 08:42:31.671829'),(72,'crop_images/552db351140543ed82de6a903037adcf.jpg','Shiitake Mushroom','Healthy',95,'[\"Healthy and uniform fruiting body development\", \"Consistent cap coloration without discoloration or lesions\", \"Intact and firm texture of mushrooms\", \"Clean substrate blocks free from visible mold contamination\", \"Vigorous mycelial growth visible on substrate blocks\"]','Healthy',97,'Low','{\"soil\": \"Well-drained, slightly acidic to neutral soil, pH 5.5-6.5, rich in organic matter\", \"family\": \"Polyporaceae\", \"origin\": \"East Asia, specifically China and Japan\", \"climate\": \"Mild, temperate climate with moderate temperatures, 10-25°C\", \"crop_name\": \"Shiitake Mushroom\", \"description\": \"Shiitake Mushroom is a highly valued edible mushroom species, prized for its rich, earthy flavor and firm texture. Cultivation practices involve inoculating logs or stumps with Lentinula edodes mycelium, followed by periodic watering and maintenance. Shiitake Mushroom is a significant economic crop, with high demand in the culinary and pharmaceutical industries. Its cultivation has also been explored for its potential to promote sustainable forest management and reduce waste.\", \"growth_duration\": \"120-180 days from inoculation\", \"scientific_name\": \"Lentinula edodes\", \"water_requirement\": \"Low to moderate, 300-500 mm per season\"}','{\"causes\": [\"Optimal growing conditions for Shiitake Mushroom\", \"Adequate moisture and temperature\", \"Proper substrate and nutrient availability\"], \"pathogen\": \"None\", \"symptoms\": [\"Normal color and texture of Shiitake Mushroom mycelium and fruiting bodies\", \"No visible signs of decay or rot\", \"No unusual odors or discoloration\", \"Typical growth patterns and development\"], \"treatment\": [], \"prevention\": [\"Maintain optimal growing conditions\", \"Monitor substrate and nutrient levels\", \"Ensure proper moisture and temperature control\"], \"precautions\": [], \"disease_name\": \"Healthy\", \"affected_areas\": [\"mycelium\", \"fruiting bodies\"], \"disease_progression\": \"No progression or spread, as Healthy is a normal state of Shiitake Mushroom growth\", \"recommended_actions\": [\"Continue monitoring growing conditions and substrate quality\", \"Adjust growing conditions as necessary to maintain optimal health\", \"Maintain good sanitation and hygiene practices\"]}','{\"packaging\": \"Perforated polyethylene bags or wooden crates with adequate ventilation to prevent moisture buildup.\", \"shelf_life\": \"2-4 weeks\", \"storage_type\": \"Cold Storage\", \"humidity_range\": \"80-90% RH\", \"do_not_store_with\": \"Onions, Garlic, and other sulfur-containing crops as they can cause off-flavors in Shiitake Mushroom.\", \"temperature_range\": \"2-5°C\", \"storage_conditions\": \"Maintain high humidity, low light, and minimal ventilation. Regularly inspect for signs of spoilage.\", \"post_harvest_handling\": \"Pre-cool to 10°C within 2 hours of harvest, grade and sort based on size and quality, wash gently to prevent bruising.\", \"expected_spoilage_time\": \"1-2 weeks under poor conditions (high temperature, low humidity)\"}','{\"dosage\": \"Total 300 kg/ha (DAP 150 kg/ha + Urea 100 kg/ha + Zinc Sulphate 20 kg/ha + Copper Sulphate 10 kg/ha + Boron 1.5 kg/ha) - Split into 3 applications: 150 kg/ha at transplanting, 75 kg/ha at 20 DAT, 75 kg/ha at 40 DAT\", \"cautions\": \"Over-fertilization can lead to reduced mycelium growth, lower yield, and increased risk of disease. Regular soil testing is recommended to avoid over-fertilization.\", \"npk_ratio\": \"150:100:100 kg/hectare (basal dose) + 75:50:50 kg/hectare (top dressing at 20 DAT) + 50:33:33 kg/hectare (top dressing at 40 DAT)\", \"micronutrients\": \"Zinc Sulphate 20 kg/ha, Copper Sulphate 10 kg/ha, Boron 1.5 kg/ha\", \"deficiency_signs\": \"Yellowing or pale coloration of the mycelium, reduced growth rate, and lower yield\", \"application_method\": \"Drip fertigation\", \"application_timing\": \"Basal dose at transplanting, top dressing at 20 and 40 days after transplanting (DAT)\", \"organic_alternatives\": \"FYM (Farm Yard Manure) 20 t/ha, Vermicompost 10 t/ha\", \"recommended_fertilizer\": \"DAP (Diammonium Phosphate) + Urea\"}','{\"harvest_method\": \"Manual hand-picking\", \"harvest_duration\": \"6-12 months after inoculation\", \"best_harvest_time\": \"Early morning, when the humidity is high and the temperature is cool, to minimize damage to the delicate caps\", \"equipment_required\": [\"Gloves to protect hands from spores\", \"Twine or string to tie mushroom stems\", \"Measuring tape to monitor fruit cap size\"], \"harvest_indicators\": [\"Fruit cap expansion and color change to a brown or tan color\", \"Firmness test: caps should be firm but not hard\", \"Leaf senescence: leaves turn yellow and wilt\", \"Fruit cap size: 5-10 cm in diameter\"], \"post_harvest_losses\": \"Typical post-harvest loss: 10-20%, can be reduced by storing mushrooms in a cool, dry place with high humidity\", \"pre_harvest_interval\": \"At least 7 days after pesticide application\", \"yield_considerations\": \"Expected yield: 10-20 kg/m³ under good conditions, 5-10 kg/m³ under poor conditions\", \"expected_harvest_date\": \"September-October\"}','{\"error\": \"Open-Meteo unreachable\", \"current\": {\"rain_mm\": 0.0, \"condition\": \"Data unavailable\", \"feels_like_c\": 26.0, \"temperature_c\": 25.0, \"wind_speed_kmh\": 15.0, \"humidity_percent\": 65, \"precipitation_mm\": 0.0, \"wind_direction_deg\": 180, \"cloud_cover_percent\": 30}, \"latitude\": 28.6139, \"timezone\": \"UTC\", \"longitude\": 77.209, \"fetched_at\": \"2026-06-11T08:45:43.337733Z\", \"forecast_7_days\": [], \"agricultural_advisory\": [\"Weather service temporarily unavailable.\"]}','{\"ai_advisory\": {\"harvest_advice\": \"Harvest mushrooms when the caps are fully expanded and the stems are firm, typically 6-12 months after inoculation.\", \"storage_advice\": \"Store harvested mushrooms in a cool, humid environment, such as a cold storage room, at a temperature range of 2-5°C and humidity range of 80-90% RH.\", \"fertilizer_advice\": \"Apply the recommended fertilizer, DAP (Diammonium Phosphate) + Urea, at the specified rates, and consider adding micronutrients such as Zinc Sulphate, Copper Sulphate, and Boron.\", \"immediate_actions\": [\"Immediate Action 1: Maintain optimal temperature and humidity levels for Shiitake mushroom growth, between 15-20°C and 70-80% relative humidity.\", \"Immediate Action 2: Ensure proper air circulation and exchange to prevent CO2 buildup and maintain a healthy environment.\"], \"irrigation_advice\": \"Maintain a consistent and optimal moisture level, avoiding overwatering, which can lead to disease and contamination.\", \"farmer_action_plan\": {\"day_1\": [\"Monitor temperature and humidity levels\", \"Check for any signs of disease or pests\"], \"day_2_7\": [\"Maintain optimal growing conditions\", \"Apply fertilizer as recommended\"], \"week_2_4\": [\"Continue to monitor crop health\", \"Implement IPM strategies as needed\"], \"long_term\": [\"Plan for future harvests and crop rotations\", \"Consider expanding or diversifying mushroom production\"]}, \"weather_precautions\": [\"Weather Precaution 1: Protect the crop from extreme temperatures, above 25°C or below 10°C, which can stress the mushrooms and increase disease susceptibility.\", \"Weather Precaution 2: Ensure adequate ventilation and air circulation to prevent moisture buildup and reduce the risk of disease.\"], \"disease_management_plan\": [\"Step 1: Continue to monitor the crop for any signs of disease, such as discoloration, lesions, or abnormal growth patterns.\", \"Step 2: Implement integrated pest management (IPM) strategies, including cultural, biological, and chemical controls, to prevent disease outbreaks.\"]}, \"market_insights\": {\"price_trend\": \"Stable\", \"demand_trend\": \"Moderate\", \"nearby_markets\": [\"Local Market\", \"Regional Market\"], \"best_selling_time\": \"September-October, during the peak harvest season\", \"current_market_price\": \"₹200-250/kg\", \"expected_price_movement\": \"Prices are expected to remain stable in the next 30 days, with a potential increase during the peak harvest season.\"}, \"overall_summary\": {\"top_risks\": [\"Risk 1: Disease outbreaks due to inadequate monitoring or control measures.\", \"Risk 2: Environmental stressors, such as extreme temperatures or moisture levels, which can impact mushroom growth and quality.\"], \"crop_status\": \"Healthy\", \"health_score\": \"97.0/100\", \"urgency_level\": \"Low\", \"disease_status\": \"Healthy\", \"final_conclusion\": \"The Shiitake mushroom crop is currently healthy, with a high health score and no visible signs of disease. However, it is essential to continue monitoring the crop and implementing IPM strategies to prevent disease outbreaks and maintain optimal growing conditions. With proper care and management, the crop is expected to thrive, and the farmer can anticipate a successful harvest.\", \"key_recommendations\": [\"Recommendation 1: Continue to monitor the crop closely for any signs of disease or stress.\", \"Recommendation 2: Implement IPM strategies and maintain optimal growing conditions to promote healthy mushroom growth.\"]}, \"weather_analysis\": {\"humidity\": \"65%\", \"wind_speed\": \"15.0 km/h\", \"weather_risks\": [\"Risk 1: High temperatures may stress the mushrooms and increase disease susceptibility.\", \"Risk 2: Low humidity may lead to moisture stress and reduce mushroom growth.\"], \"harvest_advisory\": \"Harvesting can proceed as scheduled, but be aware of the potential for moisture stress and take steps to maintain optimal humidity levels.\", \"rainfall_forecast\": \"Precipitation: 0.0 mm, Data unavailable\", \"spraying_advisory\": \"It is not recommended to spray pesticides or fungicides today due to the high wind speed and potential for drift or runoff.\", \"current_temperature\": \"25.0°C\", \"weather_recommendations\": [\"Recommendation 1: Provide shade or cooling measures to reduce temperature stress.\", \"Recommendation 2: Increase humidity levels through misting or irrigation to maintain optimal growing conditions.\"]}}','[{\"content\": \"Integrated Pest Management (IPM) principles: 1. Cultural control: Crop rotation, resistant varieties, sanitation. 2. Biological control: Predatory insects, Bt, Trichoderma. 3. Chemical control: Last resort, use registered pesticides at correct dosage. 4. Monitoring: Regular scouting every 5–7 days.\", \"metadata\": {\"type\": \"ipm\", \"source\": \"fao.org\"}, \"relevance\": 1.3696}, {\"content\": \"Powdery Mildew affects many crops including wheat, grapes, and cucurbits. White powdery coating appears on leaves and stems. Management: Apply sulfur-based fungicides. Improve air circulation. Avoid excess nitrogen fertilization.\", \"metadata\": {\"crop\": \"Wheat\", \"source\": \"usda.gov\", \"disease\": \"Powdery Mildew\"}, \"relevance\": 1.4854}, {\"content\": \"Rice Blast (Pyricularia oryzae) is the most destructive rice disease globally. Symptoms: diamond-shaped lesions on leaves, neck rot at panicle. Management: Balanced nitrogen, silicon fertilization, fungicide sprays at boot stage.\", \"metadata\": {\"crop\": \"Rice\", \"source\": \"cgiar.org\", \"disease\": \"Rice Blast\"}, \"relevance\": 1.5049}, {\"content\": \"Banana Sigatoka disease (Mycosphaerella fijiensis) management: Remove and destroy infected leaves. Apply systemic fungicides (propiconazole). Maintain plant spacing for air circulation. Banana requires 13–15 months from planting to harvest. Storage: 13–14°C, 90–95% RH. Shelf life: 1–4 weeks.\", \"metadata\": {\"crop\": \"Banana\", \"source\": \"fao.org\", \"disease\": \"Sigatoka\"}, \"relevance\": 1.5352}]',28.6139,77.209,19.45,'completed','','2026-06-11 08:45:29.501165','2026-06-11 08:45:48.964232'),(73,'crop_images/c20eeef6b6c043af839cebb580a2440a.jpg','Onion','None',85,'[\"Browning of leaf tips\", \"Yellowing of older leaves\", \"Uneven plant growth and vigor\", \"Standing water in furrows (indicating potential waterlogging)\", \"Presence of significant weed competition\"]','Stressed',72,'Medium','{\"soil\": \"Well-drained, fertile soil with pH 6.0-7.0\", \"family\": \"Amaryllidaceae\", \"origin\": \"Central Asia and the Middle East\", \"climate\": \"Temperate climate, 15-25°C\", \"crop_name\": \"Onion\", \"description\": \"Onion is a widely cultivated crop for its edible bulbs, which are rich in fiber, vitamins, and minerals. It is an important crop in many parts of the world, particularly in India and China, where it is used as a flavoring agent and a medicine. Onion cultivation practices involve careful selection of varieties, proper irrigation, and pest management to prevent diseases such as downy mildew and pink root. The economic value of onion is significant, with global production valued at over $20 billion annually.\", \"growth_duration\": \"70-120 days from transplanting\", \"scientific_name\": \"Allium cepa\", \"water_requirement\": \"Moderate, 400-600 mm per season\"}','{\"causes\": [], \"pathogen\": \"\", \"symptoms\": [], \"treatment\": [], \"prevention\": [\"Proper crop rotation\", \"Maintain good sanitation and hygiene practices in the field\", \"Avoid overwatering\"], \"precautions\": [], \"disease_name\": \"None\", \"affected_areas\": [], \"disease_progression\": \"\", \"recommended_actions\": [\"Monitor the field regularly for any signs of disease\", \"Maintain accurate records of crop health and weather conditions\", \"Consult with a plant pathologist or agricultural expert if any issues arise\"]}','{\"packaging\": \"Perforated polyethylene bags or wooden crates with breathable liners\", \"shelf_life\": \"8-12 weeks\", \"storage_type\": \"Cold Storage\", \"humidity_range\": \"80-90% RH\", \"do_not_store_with\": \"Potatoes (due to risk of sprout induction), Tomatoes (due to risk of ethylene production)\", \"temperature_range\": \"0-5°C\", \"storage_conditions\": \"Ventilation: minimal; Light: low to moderate; Sanitation: clean and dry storage area\", \"post_harvest_handling\": \"Pre-cooling: within 2 hours of harvest; Grading and sorting: based on size and quality; Washing: not recommended due to potential for bruising\", \"expected_spoilage_time\": \"2-4 weeks under poor conditions (e.g. high temperature, high humidity)\"}','{\"dosage\": \"Total 300 kg/ha (DAP 150 kg/ha + Urea 150 kg/ha)\", \"cautions\": \"Over-fertilization can lead to excessive bulb formation, reduced flavor and quality. Monitor soil pH and adjust fertilizer application accordingly.\", \"npk_ratio\": \"150:75:75 kg/ha (Basal dose at transplanting) + 75:37.5:37.5 kg/ha (Top dressing at 20 DAT) + 75:37.5:37.5 kg/ha (Top dressing at 40 DAT)\", \"micronutrients\": \"Zinc Sulphate 20 kg/ha, Boron 2 kg/ha\", \"deficiency_signs\": \"Yellowing of leaves, stunted growth, reduced bulb formation\", \"application_method\": \"Broadcast + incorporation\", \"application_timing\": \"Basal dose at transplanting, top dressing at 20 and 40 days after transplanting (DAT)\", \"organic_alternatives\": \"FYM (Farm Yard Manure) 25 t/ha, Vermicompost 10 t/ha\", \"recommended_fertilizer\": \"DAP (Diammonium Phosphate) + Urea\"}','{\"harvest_method\": \"Manual hand-picking\", \"harvest_duration\": \"60-80 DAT\", \"best_harvest_time\": \"Early morning when the sun is not intense to prevent moisture loss and damage to the bulbs\", \"equipment_required\": [\"Sharp, clean knives or pruning shears for cutting the neck of the onion\", \"Baskets or containers for collecting the harvested onions\", \"Gloves for protecting hands from the sulfur compounds in the onions\"], \"harvest_indicators\": [\"Fruit color change from green to yellow or red\", \"Firmness test: onions become harder and less yielding to pressure\", \"Leaf senescence: leaves turn yellow and wilt\", \"Neck diameter: the diameter of the neck of the onion bulb increases\"], \"post_harvest_losses\": \"Typical post-harvest loss percentage: 5-10%, can be reduced by proper curing and storage\", \"pre_harvest_interval\": \"At least 14 days after pesticide application to ensure the chemical has broken down and is no longer present on the onions\", \"yield_considerations\": \"Expected yield per hectare: 25-30 tons under good conditions, 15-20 tons under poor conditions\", \"expected_harvest_date\": \"June-July for Kharif, October-November for Rabi\"}','{\"error\": \"Open-Meteo unreachable\", \"current\": {\"rain_mm\": 0.0, \"condition\": \"Data unavailable\", \"feels_like_c\": 26.0, \"temperature_c\": 25.0, \"wind_speed_kmh\": 15.0, \"humidity_percent\": 65, \"precipitation_mm\": 0.0, \"wind_direction_deg\": 180, \"cloud_cover_percent\": 30}, \"latitude\": 28.6139, \"timezone\": \"UTC\", \"longitude\": 77.209, \"fetched_at\": \"2026-06-11T09:21:39.123282Z\", \"forecast_7_days\": [], \"agricultural_advisory\": [\"Weather service temporarily unavailable.\"]}','{\"ai_advisory\": {\"harvest_advice\": \"Harvest the onions when they are mature and the tops have fallen over, to minimize damage and ensure the best quality.\", \"storage_advice\": \"Store the onions in a cool, dry, and well-ventilated area to maintain their quality and shelf life.\", \"fertilizer_advice\": \"Apply the recommended fertilizer, DAP (Diammonium Phosphate) + Urea, at the specified dosage to promote healthy growth and development.\", \"immediate_actions\": [\"Immediate Action 1: Inspect the field to identify and remove any weeds that are competing with the onion plants for water and nutrients.\", \"Immediate Action 2: Check the irrigation system to ensure that it is functioning properly and not causing waterlogging in the furrows.\"], \"irrigation_advice\": \"Irrigate the field carefully to avoid waterlogging, which can exacerbate stress and increase the risk of disease.\", \"farmer_action_plan\": {\"day_1\": [\"Inspect the field for weeds and remove them\", \"Check the irrigation system\"], \"day_2_7\": [\"Apply the recommended fertilizer\", \"Monitor the field for disease symptoms\"], \"week_2_4\": [\"Implement good agricultural practices\", \"Monitor the weather forecast\"], \"long_term\": [\"Plan for crop rotation\", \"Consider using resistant varieties\"]}, \"weather_precautions\": [\"Weather Precaution 1: Be prepared for potential rainfall and take steps to prevent waterlogging in the field.\", \"Weather Precaution 2: Monitor the temperature and humidity levels to prevent heat stress and promote healthy growth.\"], \"disease_management_plan\": [\"Step 1: Monitor the field regularly for any signs of disease, such as yellowing or browning of leaves, and take action promptly if any symptoms are observed.\", \"Step 2: Implement good agricultural practices, such as crop rotation, sanitation, and biological control, to prevent the spread of disease.\"]}, \"market_insights\": {\"price_trend\": \"Stable\", \"demand_trend\": \"Moderate\", \"nearby_markets\": [\"Market Name A\", \"Market Name B\"], \"best_selling_time\": \"June-July for Kharif, October-November for Rabi\", \"current_market_price\": \"₹40-50/kg\", \"expected_price_movement\": \"The price is expected to remain stable in the next 30 days.\"}, \"overall_summary\": {\"top_risks\": [\"Risk 1: Waterlogging due to potential rainfall\", \"Risk 2: Heat stress due to high temperature\"], \"crop_status\": \"Stressed\", \"health_score\": \"72.0/100\", \"urgency_level\": \"Medium\", \"disease_status\": \"None\", \"final_conclusion\": \"The onion crop is currently stressed due to waterlogging and heat stress, but there are no signs of disease. The farmer should take immediate action to inspect the field, remove weeds, and check the irrigation system. The farmer should also implement good agricultural practices, such as crop rotation and biological control, to prevent the spread of disease. With proper care and management, the crop can recover and produce a good yield.\", \"key_recommendations\": [\"Recommendation 1: Inspect the field regularly for disease symptoms and take action promptly\", \"Recommendation 2: Implement good agricultural practices to prevent the spread of disease\"]}, \"weather_analysis\": {\"humidity\": \"65%\", \"wind_speed\": \"15.0 km/h\", \"weather_risks\": [\"Risk 1: Heat stress due to high temperature\", \"Risk 2: Waterlogging due to potential rainfall\"], \"harvest_advisory\": \"It is not necessary to harvest the onions early, but it is recommended to monitor the weather forecast and be prepared for potential rainfall.\", \"rainfall_forecast\": \"Precipitation: 0.0 mm, Data unavailable\", \"spraying_advisory\": \"It is not recommended to spray pesticides/fungicides today due to the wind speed and potential rainfall.\", \"current_temperature\": \"25.0°C\", \"weather_recommendations\": [\"Recommendation 1: Irrigate the field carefully to avoid waterlogging\", \"Recommendation 2: Monitor the temperature and humidity levels to prevent heat stress\"]}}','[{\"content\": \"Cotton (Gossypium hirsutum) bollworm management: Inspect weekly during boll formation. Use pheromone traps for monitoring. Apply Bt-based biopesticides at early instar stage. Recommended NPK: 120:60:60 kg/ha with micronutrients.\", \"metadata\": {\"crop\": \"Cotton\", \"source\": \"icar.org.in\", \"disease\": \"Bollworm\"}, \"relevance\": 1.3738}, {\"content\": \"Integrated Pest Management (IPM) principles: 1. Cultural control: Crop rotation, resistant varieties, sanitation. 2. Biological control: Predatory insects, Bt, Trichoderma. 3. Chemical control: Last resort, use registered pesticides at correct dosage. 4. Monitoring: Regular scouting every 5–7 days.\", \"metadata\": {\"type\": \"ipm\", \"source\": \"fao.org\"}, \"relevance\": 1.4269}, {\"content\": \"Late Blight (Phytophthora infestans) is a devastating disease of tomato and potato. Symptoms include dark, water-soaked lesions on leaves and stems that rapidly expand. Management: Apply copper-based fungicides. Remove infected plants. Use resistant varieties. Avoid overhead irrigation.\", \"metadata\": {\"crop\": \"Tomato\", \"source\": \"plantvillage.psu.edu\", \"disease\": \"Late Blight\"}, \"relevance\": 1.4909}, {\"content\": \"Tomato cultivation requires well-drained loamy soil with pH 6.0–7.0. Scientific name: Solanum lycopersicum. Growth duration: 60–90 days after transplanting. NPK recommendation: 120:60:60 kg/ha. Requires staking for indeterminate varieties.\", \"metadata\": {\"crop\": \"Tomato\", \"type\": \"overview\", \"source\": \"icar.org.in\"}, \"relevance\": 1.527}]',28.6139,77.209,70.26,'completed','','2026-06-11 09:20:51.256743','2026-06-11 09:22:01.518482'),(74,'crop_images/3bf83956aa2045989595c54ef7c2de82.jpg','Leafy Green Vegetable','Healthy',85,'[]','Healthy',97,'Low','{\"soil\": \"Well-drained, fertile soil with pH 6.0-7.0\", \"family\": \"Amaranthaceae, Asteraceae, Brassicaceae\", \"origin\": \"South America, Mediterranean, Asia\", \"climate\": \"Temperate, subtropical, 15-25°C\", \"crop_name\": \"Leafy Green Vegetable\", \"description\": \"Leafy green vegetables are a crucial component of a healthy diet, providing essential vitamins, minerals, and antioxidants. They are widely cultivated and consumed globally, with major producers including China, the United States, and India. Leafy greens are typically grown using conventional or organic farming practices, with a focus on maintaining soil health, optimizing water use, and minimizing pest and disease pressure. The economic value of leafy greens lies in their high demand, relatively low production costs, and potential for year-round production in controlled environments.\", \"growth_duration\": \"40-70 days from direct sowing or 60-90 days from transplanting\", \"scientific_name\": \"Amaranthus spp. (Lactuca sativa, Brassica oleracea, Spinacia oleracea)\", \"water_requirement\": \"Moderate, 300-500 mm per season\"}','{\"causes\": [\"Optimal growing conditions\", \"Adequate water and nutrient supply\", \"Balanced soil pH and nutrient levels\"], \"pathogen\": \"None\", \"symptoms\": [\"Normal leaf color and texture\", \"No visible signs of disease or pests\", \"Optimal growth and development\", \"No premature senescence or leaf drop\"], \"treatment\": [], \"prevention\": [\"Maintain optimal growing conditions\", \"Monitor and adjust nutrient and water supply\", \"Implement integrated pest management practices\"], \"precautions\": [\"Avoid overuse of fertilizers and pesticides\", \"Monitor for potential pests and diseases\"], \"disease_name\": \"Healthy\", \"affected_areas\": [\"leaf\", \"stem\", \"root\", \"fruit\", \"flower\"], \"disease_progression\": \"No disease progression occurs as Healthy is a state of optimal plant health.\", \"recommended_actions\": [\"Conduct regular soil and plant tissue tests\", \"Adjust irrigation and fertilization schedules\", \"Implement crop rotation and sanitation practices\"]}','{\"packaging\": \"Perforated polyethylene bags or wooden crates lined with moisture-absorbing materials\", \"shelf_life\": \"10-14 days\", \"storage_type\": \"Controlled Atmosphere Storage / Cold Storage\", \"humidity_range\": \"90-95% RH\", \"do_not_store_with\": \"Onions, as they release ethylene gas that can cause spoilage in Leafy Greens. Also, avoid storing with strong-smelling crops, as they can transfer odors to Leafy Greens.\", \"temperature_range\": \"0-5°C\", \"storage_conditions\": \"Maintain 90-95% RH, 0-5°C, and 5-10% CO2. Ensure minimal light exposure and maintain good ventilation.\", \"post_harvest_handling\": \"Pre-cool to 5°C within 2 hours of harvest, grade and sort immediately, wash in chlorinated water (50 ppm), and dry with clean towels.\", \"expected_spoilage_time\": \"3-5 days under poor conditions (high temperature, high humidity, and poor ventilation)\"}','{\"dosage\": \"Total 300 kg/ha, Basal dose 150 kg/ha at transplanting, Top dressing 75 kg/ha at 20 DAT, 50 kg/ha at 40 DAT, 25 kg/ha at 60 DAT\", \"cautions\": \"Over-fertilization can lead to nutrient imbalances, soil pollution, and reduced crop yields. Regular soil testing is recommended to avoid over-fertilization.\", \"npk_ratio\": \"150:75:75 kg/ha\", \"micronutrients\": \"Zinc Sulphate 20 kg/ha, Boron 2 kg/ha, Magnesium Sulphate 10 kg/ha\", \"deficiency_signs\": \"Yellowing of leaves, stunted growth, reduced leaf size, and marginal scorching\", \"application_method\": \"Broadcast + incorporation\", \"application_timing\": \"Basal dose at transplanting, Top dressing at 20, 40, 60 days after transplanting (DAT)\", \"organic_alternatives\": \"FYM 25 t/ha, Vermicompost 10 t/ha, Compost Tea\", \"recommended_fertilizer\": \"DAP + Urea\"}','{\"harvest_method\": \"Manual hand-picking\", \"harvest_duration\": \"40-55 DAT\", \"best_harvest_time\": \"Early morning when leaves are turgid and least prone to damage\", \"equipment_required\": [\"Gloves for hand protection\", \"Sharp knives or pruning shears for clean cuts\", \"Baskets or containers for leaf collection\"], \"harvest_indicators\": [\"Leaf color change from green to yellow or bronze\", \"Leaf texture change to tender and slightly crunchy\", \"Leaf size and density increase\", \"Stem color change to a lighter shade\"], \"post_harvest_losses\": \"Typical post-harvest loss: 10-15% due to moisture loss and mechanical damage; reduce by using breathable packaging and gentle handling\", \"pre_harvest_interval\": \"3-5 days after pesticide application\", \"yield_considerations\": \"Expected yield: 20-30 tons per hectare under good conditions, 10-15 tons per hectare under poor conditions\", \"expected_harvest_date\": \"June-July for Kharif, October-November for Rabi\"}','{\"error\": \"Open-Meteo unreachable\", \"current\": {\"rain_mm\": 0.0, \"condition\": \"Data unavailable\", \"feels_like_c\": 26.0, \"temperature_c\": 25.0, \"wind_speed_kmh\": 15.0, \"humidity_percent\": 65, \"precipitation_mm\": 0.0, \"wind_direction_deg\": 180, \"cloud_cover_percent\": 30}, \"latitude\": 28.6139, \"timezone\": \"UTC\", \"longitude\": 77.209, \"fetched_at\": \"2026-06-11T09:25:52.774714Z\", \"forecast_7_days\": [], \"agricultural_advisory\": [\"Weather service temporarily unavailable.\"]}','{\"ai_advisory\": {\"harvest_advice\": \"Harvest the crop at the optimal time, when the leaves are at their peak freshness and quality, typically between 40-55 days after transplanting\", \"storage_advice\": \"Store the leafy green vegetables in a controlled atmosphere storage or cold storage at 0-5°C and 90-95% RH to maintain freshness and extend shelf life\", \"fertilizer_advice\": \"Apply the recommended fertilizer (DAP + Urea) at the specified dosage and timing to promote healthy growth and development\", \"immediate_actions\": [\"Immediate Action 1: Continue to monitor the crop for any signs of disease or pests\", \"Immediate Action 2: Maintain optimal growing conditions, including temperature, humidity, and light exposure\"], \"irrigation_advice\": \"Water the crop regularly, but avoid overwatering, which can lead to disease and root rot. Maintain a consistent moisture level, taking into account the current weather conditions\", \"farmer_action_plan\": {\"day_1\": [\"Inspect the crop for any signs of disease or pests\", \"Maintain optimal growing conditions\"], \"day_2_7\": [\"Continue to monitor the crop and maintain optimal growing conditions\", \"Apply fertilizer as recommended\"], \"week_2_4\": [\"Implement IPM strategies and maintain good hygiene practices\", \"Monitor for signs of disease or pests\"], \"long_term\": [\"Plan for crop rotation and soil management to maintain soil health and reduce disease risk\", \"Continuously monitor and adjust growing conditions as needed\"]}, \"weather_precautions\": [\"Weather Precaution 1: Be prepared for potential weather extremes, such as high temperatures or unexpected rainfall, which can impact crop growth and disease susceptibility\", \"Weather Precaution 2: Monitor wind speed and direction to minimize the risk of disease spread and damage to the crop\"], \"disease_management_plan\": [\"Step 1: Since the crop is currently healthy, focus on preventive measures such as maintaining good hygiene, removing weeds, and ensuring adequate air circulation\", \"Step 2: Implement integrated pest management (IPM) strategies, including crop rotation, biological control, and cultural controls\"]}, \"market_insights\": {\"price_trend\": \"Stable\", \"demand_trend\": \"Moderate\", \"nearby_markets\": [\"Local Market A\", \"Regional Market B\"], \"best_selling_time\": \"June-July for Kharif, October-November for Rabi\", \"current_market_price\": \"₹40-50/kg\", \"expected_price_movement\": \"The price is expected to remain stable in the next 30 days, with a potential increase during peak demand seasons\"}, \"overall_summary\": {\"top_risks\": [\"Risk 1: Disease susceptibility due to weather extremes or poor growing conditions\", \"Risk 2: Pests or insects that can damage the crop\"], \"crop_status\": \"Healthy\", \"health_score\": \"97.0/100\", \"urgency_level\": \"Low\", \"disease_status\": \"Healthy\", \"final_conclusion\": \"The leafy green vegetable crop is currently healthy, with a high health score and no visible symptoms of disease. The farmer should continue to monitor the crop and maintain optimal growing conditions to minimize the risk of disease and pests. With proper care and management, the crop is expected to remain healthy and reach its full potential, resulting in a successful harvest and a good market price.\", \"key_recommendations\": [\"Recommendation 1: Maintain optimal growing conditions and monitor the crop regularly for signs of disease or pests\", \"Recommendation 2: Implement IPM strategies and maintain good hygiene practices to minimize disease risk\"]}, \"weather_analysis\": {\"humidity\": \"65%\", \"wind_speed\": \"15.0 km/h\", \"weather_risks\": [\"Risk 1: High temperatures can lead to increased disease susceptibility and water stress\", \"Risk 2: Unexpected rainfall can lead to waterlogged soil and increased disease risk\"], \"harvest_advisory\": \"The farmer should wait to harvest the crop until the optimal time, taking into account the current weather forecast and crop condition\", \"rainfall_forecast\": \"Precipitation: 0.0 mm, Data unavailable\", \"spraying_advisory\": \"It is not recommended to spray pesticides or fungicides today due to the wind speed and potential for drift\", \"current_temperature\": \"25.0°C\", \"weather_recommendations\": [\"Recommendation 1: Maintain optimal growing conditions, including temperature and humidity control\", \"Recommendation 2: Be prepared for potential weather extremes and have a plan in place to mitigate their impact\"]}}','[{\"content\": \"General crop storage principles: Temperature and humidity control are critical. Most vegetables: 0–10°C, 85–95% RH. Grains: <15°C, <14% moisture. Fruits: 10–15°C, 85–90% RH. Use hermetic bags or cold rooms to extend shelf life.\", \"metadata\": {\"type\": \"storage\", \"source\": \"fao.org\"}, \"relevance\": 1.1995}, {\"content\": \"Powdery Mildew affects many crops including wheat, grapes, and cucurbits. White powdery coating appears on leaves and stems. Management: Apply sulfur-based fungicides. Improve air circulation. Avoid excess nitrogen fertilization.\", \"metadata\": {\"crop\": \"Wheat\", \"source\": \"usda.gov\", \"disease\": \"Powdery Mildew\"}, \"relevance\": 1.2059}, {\"content\": \"Tomato cultivation requires well-drained loamy soil with pH 6.0–7.0. Scientific name: Solanum lycopersicum. Growth duration: 60–90 days after transplanting. NPK recommendation: 120:60:60 kg/ha. Requires staking for indeterminate varieties.\", \"metadata\": {\"crop\": \"Tomato\", \"type\": \"overview\", \"source\": \"icar.org.in\"}, \"relevance\": 1.2335}, {\"content\": \"Maize (Zea mays) grey leaf spot disease. Symptoms: rectangular grey-brown lesions parallel to leaf veins. Management: Crop rotation, resistant hybrids, triazole fungicides. Maize NPK: 150:75:75 kg/ha. Harvest at 25–30% grain moisture.\", \"metadata\": {\"crop\": \"Maize\", \"source\": \"cgiar.org\", \"disease\": \"Grey Leaf Spot\"}, \"relevance\": 1.2489}]',28.6139,77.209,36.53,'completed','','2026-06-11 09:25:21.434946','2026-06-11 09:25:57.974679'),(75,'crop_images/80852531383f4bacaf02755e4e692358.png','Bamboo','Healthy',70,'[]','Healthy',97,'Low','{\"soil\": \"Well-drained loamy soil, pH 6.0-7.0, rich in organic matter\", \"family\": \"Poaceae\", \"origin\": \"Southeast Asia\", \"climate\": \"Warm tropical, 20-30°C, high humidity\", \"crop_name\": \"Bamboo\", \"description\": \"Bamboo is an ecologically and economically important crop, providing food, shelter, and income for millions of people worldwide. It is cultivated for its timber, shoots, and other products, with India being the largest producer. Bamboo is a low-maintenance crop that can thrive in poor soil conditions, making it an ideal crop for small-scale farmers and agroforestry systems. Its economic value lies in its versatility, durability, and sustainability, making it a valuable crop for rural development and environmental conservation.\", \"growth_duration\": \"3-5 years from germination\", \"scientific_name\": \"Bambusa tulda\", \"water_requirement\": \"High, 800-1200 mm per season\"}','{\"causes\": [\"Optimal growing conditions, including adequate water, nutrients, and sunlight\", \"Proper soil pH and nutrient balance\", \"Regular pruning and maintenance to promote healthy growth\"], \"pathogen\": \"None\", \"symptoms\": [\"Normal green coloration and firm texture of bamboo culms\", \"Absence of visible lesions, discoloration, or other signs of disease\", \"Healthy growth and development of new shoots and leaves\", \"No signs of stress or nutrient deficiency\"], \"treatment\": [], \"prevention\": [\"Maintain optimal growing conditions, including adequate water, nutrients, and sunlight\", \"Monitor soil pH and nutrient balance, and adjust as necessary\", \"Regularly prune and maintain bamboo to promote healthy growth\"], \"precautions\": [\"No special precautions are necessary for healthy bamboo\", \"Avoid over-pruning or damaging bamboo culms, which can lead to stress and disease\"], \"disease_name\": \"Healthy\", \"affected_areas\": [\"leaf\", \"stem\", \"root\", \"flower\"], \"disease_progression\": \"Healthy bamboo does not spread disease; it is a normal state of the plant.\", \"recommended_actions\": [\"Continue to monitor bamboo for signs of disease or stress\", \"Maintain regular pruning and maintenance schedule\", \"Consider consulting with a plant expert or conducting soil tests to ensure optimal growing conditions\"]}','{\"packaging\": \"Perforated polyethylene bags or wooden crates lined with a moisture-absorbing material\", \"shelf_life\": \"2-4 weeks\", \"storage_type\": \"Hermetic Bags\", \"humidity_range\": \"85-90% RH\", \"do_not_store_with\": \"Do not store bamboo alongside crops with high moisture content, such as fruits and vegetables, as it may lead to mold and rot.\", \"temperature_range\": \"10-13°C\", \"storage_conditions\": \"Store in a cool, dry, dark area with minimal ventilation. Maintain a consistent temperature and humidity level.\", \"post_harvest_handling\": \"Pre-cool to 10°C within 2 hours of harvest, sort and grade, wash with clean water to remove dirt and debris.\", \"expected_spoilage_time\": \"1-2 weeks under poor conditions (high temperature and humidity)\"}','{\"dosage\": \"Total 300 kg/ha, split into 2 applications: 150 kg/ha at transplanting and 150 kg/ha at 6 months after transplanting\", \"cautions\": \"Avoid over-fertilization, as it may cause nutrient imbalance and water pollution\", \"npk_ratio\": \"150:75:75 kg/hectare for seedling stage, 120:60:60 kg/hectare for mature stage\", \"micronutrients\": \"Zinc Sulphate 25 kg/ha, Boron 2 kg/ha, Copper 2 kg/ha\", \"deficiency_signs\": \"Yellowing of leaves, stunted growth, reduced culm diameter\", \"application_method\": \"Drip fertigation\", \"application_timing\": \"Basal dose at transplanting, top dressing at 20, 40, 60 days after transplanting (DAT)\", \"organic_alternatives\": \"FYM (Farm Yard Manure) 25 t/ha, Vermicompost 10 t/ha\", \"recommended_fertilizer\": \"NPK 19-19-19 + DAP (Diammonium Phosphate)\"}','{\"harvest_method\": \"Mechanical harvesting using a bamboo harvester or manual hand-picking\", \"harvest_duration\": \"3-5 years after planting\", \"best_harvest_time\": \"Early morning when the dew is still present, as it helps in easy removal of the culms from the soil\", \"equipment_required\": [\"Bamboo harvester or manual pruning shears\", \"Culm cutter\", \"Tractor or manual labor for transportation\"], \"harvest_indicators\": [\"Culm diameter increase\", \"Node color change from green to yellow\", \"Culm straightening and stiffening\", \"Shoots turning yellow and drying\"], \"post_harvest_losses\": \"Typical post-harvest loss: 10-15%, can be reduced by proper handling and storage\", \"pre_harvest_interval\": \"At least 30 days after pesticide application\", \"yield_considerations\": \"Average yield: 20-30 tons per hectare under good conditions, 10-20 tons per hectare under poor conditions\", \"expected_harvest_date\": \"March-April\"}','{\"error\": \"Open-Meteo unreachable\", \"current\": {\"rain_mm\": 0.0, \"condition\": \"Data unavailable\", \"feels_like_c\": 26.0, \"temperature_c\": 25.0, \"wind_speed_kmh\": 15.0, \"humidity_percent\": 65, \"precipitation_mm\": 0.0, \"wind_direction_deg\": 180, \"cloud_cover_percent\": 30}, \"latitude\": 28.6139, \"timezone\": \"UTC\", \"longitude\": 77.209, \"fetched_at\": \"2026-06-11T09:30:42.663484Z\", \"forecast_7_days\": [], \"agricultural_advisory\": [\"Weather service temporarily unavailable.\"]}','{\"ai_advisory\": {\"harvest_advice\": \"Given the crop\'s healthy status and assuming it\'s near the expected harvest duration of 3-5 years, prepare for harvest by monitoring for indicators such as culm diameter increase and node color change.\", \"storage_advice\": \"Given the healthy state of the crop, store harvested bamboo in hermetic bags at 10-13°C with 85-90% RH to maintain quality.\", \"fertilizer_advice\": \"Maintain the recommended fertilizer application schedule of NPK 19-19-19 + DAP, with additional micronutrients as specified, to support healthy growth.\", \"immediate_actions\": [\"Immediate Action 1: Continue to monitor the crop for any signs of disease or pests, given the current healthy status.\", \"Immediate Action 2: Ensure proper storage conditions are maintained for any harvested bamboo to prevent deterioration.\"], \"irrigation_advice\": \"With the current weather conditions showing no rainfall, ensure that the bamboo receives adequate moisture, possibly through controlled irrigation, to prevent water stress.\", \"farmer_action_plan\": {\"day_1\": [\"Inspect the crop for any signs of disease or pests\", \"Check irrigation systems\"], \"day_2_7\": [\"Apply fertilizer as per the recommended schedule\", \"Monitor weather forecasts for any changes\"], \"week_2_4\": [\"Continue regular inspections for disease and pests\", \"Assess crop for harvest readiness\"], \"long_term\": [\"Plan for crop rotation or replanting after harvest\", \"Review and adjust fertilizer and irrigation strategies based on crop performance\"]}, \"weather_precautions\": [\"Weather Precaution 1: Be prepared for potential drought stress with the lack of rainfall, ensuring irrigation systems are ready.\", \"Weather Precaution 2: Monitor wind speeds, as high winds could potentially damage the bamboo, and take protective measures if necessary.\"], \"disease_management_plan\": [\"Step 1: Since the crop is currently healthy, focus on preventive measures such as maintaining good hygiene, removing any weeds, and ensuring adequate air circulation.\", \"Step 2: Implement a regular inspection schedule to quickly identify any potential disease outbreaks, allowing for swift action.\"]}, \"market_i