t_plan\": [\"Step 1: Implement Integrated Pest Management (IPM) principles, including cultural, biological, and chemical controls, to prevent disease onset.\", \"Step 2: Regularly inspect the crop for early detection of diseases like Powdery Mildew or Banana Sigatoka, and apply management strategies such as sulfur-based fungicides and improved air circulation if necessary.\"]}, \"market_insights\": {\"price_trend\": \"Stable\", \"demand_trend\": \"Moderate\", \"nearby_markets\": [\"Local Market A\", \"Regional Market B\"], \"best_selling_time\": \"September to October, aligning with the expected harvest period\", \"current_market_price\": \"₹200-250/kg\", \"expected_price_movement\": \"Prices are expected to remain stable in the next 30 days, with potential for slight increase during peak harvest season.\"}, \"overall_summary\": {\"top_risks\": [\"Risk 1: Disease onset due to changes in weather conditions\", \"Risk 2: Heat stress impacting crop health\"], \"crop_status\": \"Healthy\", \"health_score\": \"97.0/100\", \"urgency_level\": \"Low\", \"disease_status\": \"Healthy\", \"final_conclusion\": \"The tobacco crop is currently in a healthy state with a high health score, indicating low urgency for immediate action. However, continued monitoring for disease and pests, along with adherence to recommended irrigation, fertilization, and storage practices, is crucial to maintain crop health and maximize yield. The farmer should remain vigilant for changes in weather that could impact crop health and be prepared to implement disease management strategies as needed.\", \"key_recommendations\": [\"Recommendation 1: Continue monitoring for disease and pests, and apply IPM strategies as necessary\", \"Recommendation 2: Maintain optimal irrigation and fertilization practices\"]}, \"weather_analysis\": {\"humidity\": \"47%\", \"wind_speed\": \"19.0 km/h\", \"weather_risks\": [\"Risk 1: Heat stress due to high temperatures\", \"Risk 2: Potential for increased disease susceptibility if weather conditions change\"], \"harvest_advisory\": \"There is no immediate need to harvest early based on the current weather forecast.\", \"rainfall_forecast\": \"Precipitation: 0.0 mm, Mainly Clear\", \"spraying_advisory\": \"It is safe to spray pesticides/fungicides today given the mainly clear weather and moderate wind speed.\", \"current_temperature\": \"30.9°C\", \"weather_recommendations\": [\"Recommendation 1: Maintain adequate irrigation to prevent heat stress\", \"Recommendation 2: Monitor weather forecasts closely for any changes that could impact crop health\"]}}','[{\"content\": \"Integrated Pest Management (IPM) principles: 1. Cultural control: Crop rotation, resistant varieties, sanitation. 2. Biological control: Predatory insects, Bt, Trichoderma. 3. Chemical control: Last resort, use registered pesticides at correct dosage. 4. Monitoring: Regular scouting every 5–7 days.\", \"metadata\": {\"type\": \"ipm\", \"source\": \"fao.org\"}, \"relevance\": 1.4707}, {\"content\": \"Powdery Mildew affects many crops including wheat, grapes, and cucurbits. White powdery coating appears on leaves and stems. Management: Apply sulfur-based fungicides. Improve air circulation. Avoid excess nitrogen fertilization.\", \"metadata\": {\"crop\": \"Wheat\", \"source\": \"usda.gov\", \"disease\": \"Powdery Mildew\"}, \"relevance\": 1.4983}, {\"content\": \"Banana Sigatoka disease (Mycosphaerella fijiensis) management: Remove and destroy infected leaves. Apply systemic fungicides (propiconazole). Maintain plant spacing for air circulation. Banana requires 13–15 months from planting to harvest. Storage: 13–14°C, 90–95% RH. Shelf life: 1–4 weeks.\", \"metadata\": {\"crop\": \"Banana\", \"source\": \"fao.org\", \"disease\": \"Sigatoka\"}, \"relevance\": 1.5346}, {\"content\": \"Maize (Zea mays) grey leaf spot disease. Symptoms: rectangular grey-brown lesions parallel to leaf veins. Management: Crop rotation, resistant hybrids, triazole fungicides. Maize NPK: 150:75:75 kg/ha. Harvest at 25–30% grain moisture.\", \"metadata\": {\"crop\": \"Maize\", \"source\": \"cgiar.org\", \"disease\": \"Grey Leaf Spot\"}, \"relevance\": 1.5706}]',18.50618,73.761452,30.87,'completed','','2026-06-18 11:02:36.130378','2026-06-18 11:03:07.007523'),(94,'crop_images/a6265d717de546acac0f08d58f9421e4.webp','Onion','Healthy',95,'[]','Healthy',97,'Low','{\"soil\": \"Well-drained sandy loam or clay loam soil, pH 6.0-7.0\", \"family\": \"Amaryllidaceae\", \"origin\": \"Central Asia\", \"climate\": \"Temperate climate, 15-25°C\", \"crop_name\": \"Onion\", \"description\": \"Onion is a widely cultivated crop for its bulbs, which are rich in flavor and nutrients. It is an important crop in many parts of the world, particularly in Asia and Europe, where it is used as a vegetable and in cooking. Onion cultivation practices involve careful management of soil, water, and pests to ensure high yields and quality. The economic value of onion is significant, with global production valued at billions of dollars annually.\", \"growth_duration\": \"120-180 days from sowing\", \"scientific_name\": \"Allium cepa\", \"water_requirement\": \"Moderate, 400-600 mm per season\"}','{\"causes\": [\"Optimal growing conditions\", \"Adequate water and nutrient supply\", \"Low disease pressure\"], \"pathogen\": \"None\", \"symptoms\": [\"Normal growth and development\", \"No visible signs of disease\", \"No discoloration or lesions\", \"No reduction in yield or quality\"], \"treatment\": [\"No treatment required\", \"Monitoring for potential disease issues\", \"Maintaining good agricultural practices\"], \"prevention\": [\"Providing optimal growing conditions\", \"Maintaining soil health\", \"Practicing good irrigation management\"], \"precautions\": [\"No specific safety precautions required\", \"Following standard agricultural safety protocols\"], \"disease_name\": \"Healthy\", \"affected_areas\": [\"leaf\", \"stem\", \"root\", \"fruit\", \"flower\"], \"disease_progression\": \"No progression or spread\", \"recommended_actions\": [\"Monitor crop health regularly\", \"Maintain accurate records of crop growth and development\", \"Consult with a plant pathologist or agricultural expert if concerns arise\"]}','{\"packaging\": \"Perforated polyethylene bags or wooden crates with ventilation to prevent moisture buildup\", \"shelf_life\": \"8-12 weeks\", \"storage_type\": \"Cold Storage\", \"humidity_range\": \"80-90% RH\", \"do_not_store_with\": \"Potatoes (due to risk of disease transmission), Tomatoes (due to risk of moisture transfer)\", \"temperature_range\": \"0-5°C\", \"storage_conditions\": \"Ventilation: minimal; Light: low; Sanitation: regular cleaning and monitoring for pests and diseases\", \"post_harvest_handling\": \"Pre-cooling to 10°C within 2 hours of harvest, grading and sorting to remove damaged onions, washing to remove soil and debris\", \"expected_spoilage_time\": \"2-3 weeks under poor conditions (high temperature and humidity)\"}','{\"dosage\": \"Total dosage: 150 kg N, 60 kg P2O5, 60 kg K2O/ha. Split schedule: Basal dose at transplanting (60 kg N, 30 kg P2O5, 30 kg K2O/ha), Top dressing at 20, 40, 60 days after transplanting (DAP 20 kg N/ha each time)\", \"cautions\": \"Over-fertilization with nitrogen can lead to increased susceptibility to diseases like pink root and neck rot. Regular soil testing is recommended to avoid over-fertilization.\", \"npk_ratio\": \"120:60:60 kg/ha (basal dose at transplanting, 60 kg N, 30 kg P2O5, 30 kg K2O/ha)\", \"micronutrients\": \"Zinc Sulphate 25 kg/ha, Boron 2 kg/ha, Copper 1 kg/ha\", \"deficiency_signs\": \"Nitrogen deficiency: Yellowing of leaves, stunted growth. Phosphorus deficiency: Purple coloration of leaves, stunted growth. Potassium deficiency: Yellowing of leaves, marginal scorching.\", \"application_method\": \"Broadcast + incorporation\", \"application_timing\": \"Basal dose at transplanting, Top dressing at 20, 40, 60 days after transplanting (DAT)\", \"organic_alternatives\": \"FYM (Farm Yard Manure) 25 t/ha, Vermicompost 10 t/ha\", \"recommended_fertilizer\": \"DAP (Diammonium Phosphate) + Urea\"}','{\"harvest_method\": \"manual hand-picking\", \"harvest_duration\": \"60-80 DAT\", \"best_harvest_time\": \"early morning to avoid heat stress and minimize moisture loss\", \"equipment_required\": [\"sharp, clean knives for cutting the neck\", \"baskets or bags for collecting the onions\", \"a fork or trowel for gently loosening the soil around the onions\"], \"harvest_indicators\": [\"fruit color change from green to yellow or red\", \"firmness test: onions are ready when they are firm and do not crush easily\", \"leaf senescence: yellowing and drying of leaves\", \"neck diameter: onions are ready when the neck diameter is about 1 inch\"], \"post_harvest_losses\": \"typical post-harvest loss percentage: 5-10%, how to reduce it: proper curing, drying, and storage\", \"pre_harvest_interval\": \"at least 14 days after pesticide application\", \"yield_considerations\": \"expected yield per hectare: 20-25 tons under good conditions, 10-15 tons under poor conditions\", \"expected_harvest_date\": \"October-November\"}','{\"current\": {\"rain_mm\": 0.0, \"condition\": \"Mainly Clear\", \"feels_like_c\": 31.0, \"temperature_c\": 30.7, \"wind_speed_kmh\": 19.0, \"humidity_percent\": 48, \"precipitation_mm\": 0.0, \"wind_direction_deg\": 274, \"cloud_cover_percent\": 27}, \"latitude\": 18.506086, \"timezone\": \"Asia/Kolkata\", \"longitude\": 73.762144, \"fetched_at\": \"2026-06-18T11:25:10.126277Z\", \"forecast_7_days\": [{\"date\": \"2026-06-18\", \"condition\": \"Light Drizzle\", \"temp_max_c\": 33.5, \"temp_min_c\": 23.2, \"wind_speed_kmh\": 19.0, \"precipitation_mm\": 0.2}, {\"date\": \"2026-06-19\", \"condition\": \"Light Drizzle\", \"temp_max_c\": 34.2, \"temp_min_c\": 22.0, \"wind_speed_kmh\": 17.5, \"precipitation_mm\": 0.3}, {\"date\": \"2026-06-20\", \"condition\": \"Thunderstorm\", \"temp_max_c\": 33.9, \"temp_min_c\": 23.0, \"wind_speed_kmh\": 18.0, \"precipitation_mm\": 3.5}, {\"date\": \"2026-06-21\", \"condition\": \"Thunderstorm\", \"temp_max_c\": 32.5, \"temp_min_c\": 23.8, \"wind_speed_kmh\": 18.7, \"precipitation_mm\": 6.7}, {\"date\": \"2026-06-22\", \"condition\": \"Thunderstorm\", \"temp_max_c\": 30.7, \"temp_min_c\": 23.5, \"wind_speed_kmh\": 14.1, \"precipitation_mm\": 10.2}, {\"date\": \"2026-06-23\", \"condition\": \"Thunderstorm with Hail\", \"temp_max_c\": 25.5, \"temp_min_c\": 22.9, \"wind_speed_kmh\": 16.1, \"precipitation_mm\": 12.3}, {\"date\": \"2026-06-24\", \"condition\": \"Light Drizzle\", \"temp_max_c\": 27.1, \"temp_min_c\": 22.1, \"wind_speed_kmh\": 19.5, \"precipitation_mm\": 1.8}], \"agricultural_advisory\": [\"✅ Weather conditions are favourable for crop growth.\"]}','{\"ai_advisory\": {\"harvest_advice\": \"Plan for harvest in 60-80 days, monitoring for indicators such as fruit color change, firmness, and leaf senescence.\", \"storage_advice\": \"Given the healthy state of the onions, store them in a cool, dry place with minimal ventilation to maintain quality and prolong shelf life.\", \"fertilizer_advice\": \"Apply the recommended fertilizer (DAP + Urea) at the specified dosage to promote healthy growth and development.\", \"immediate_actions\": [\"Immediate Action 1: Continue to monitor the crop for any signs of disease or pests, given the current healthy status.\", \"Immediate Action 2: Ensure proper irrigation management to prevent water stress, considering the current weather conditions.\"], \"irrigation_advice\": \"Water the onions deeply but infrequently to encourage deep root growth and make them more resistant to disease, taking into account the current temperature and humidity levels.\", \"farmer_action_plan\": {\"day_1\": [\"Inspect the crop for any signs of disease or pests\", \"Check irrigation systems\"], \"day_2_7\": [\"Apply fertilizer as recommended\", \"Continue monitoring for pests and diseases\"], \"week_2_4\": [\"Implement IPM practices as necessary\", \"Maintain proper irrigation and fertilization schedules\"], \"long_term\": [\"Plan for crop rotation\", \"Review and adjust the fertilization strategy based on soil test results\"]}, \"weather_precautions\": [\"Weather Precaution 1: Be prepared for potential heat stress with the current high temperature, ensuring adequate irrigation.\", \"Weather Precaution 2: Monitor for any changes in weather conditions that could lead to disease development or pest infestations.\"], \"disease_management_plan\": [\"Step 1: Maintain a strict crop rotation schedule to prevent the buildup of pathogens.\", \"Step 2: Implement integrated pest management (IPM) practices, including cultural, biological, and chemical controls as necessary.\"]}, \"market_insights\": {\"price_trend\": \"Stable\", \"demand_trend\": \"Moderate\", \"nearby_markets\": [\"Local Market A\", \"Regional Market B\"], \"best_selling_time\": \"October-November, during the peak harvest season\", \"current_market_price\": \"₹40-50/kg\", \"expected_price_movement\": \"Prices are expected to remain stable in the next 30 days, with potential for a slight increase during the peak harvest season.\"}, \"overall_summary\": {\"top_risks\": [\"Risk 1: Potential for disease development if proper management practices are not followed\", \"Risk 2: Impact of weather extremes on crop health and yield\"], \"crop_status\": \"Healthy\", \"health_score\": \"97.0/100\", \"urgency_level\": \"Low\", \"disease_status\": \"Healthy\", \"final_conclusion\": \"The onion crop is currently in a healthy state with a high health score, indicating minimal risk of disease. However, it is crucial to continue monitoring the crop and adjusting management practices as necessary to maintain its health and maximize yield. With proper care and attention to potential risks, the crop is expected to reach its full potential and provide a good harvest.\", \"key_recommendations\": [\"Recommendation 1: Continue with integrated pest management practices\", \"Recommendation 2: Monitor weather forecasts closely and adjust irrigation and other management practices accordingly\"]}, \"weather_analysis\": {\"humidity\": \"48%\", \"wind_speed\": \"19.0 km/h\", \"weather_risks\": [\"Risk 1: Heat stress due to high temperatures\", \"Risk 2: Potential for increased evapotranspiration leading to water stress\"], \"harvest_advisory\": \"There is no need to harvest early based on the current forecast; continue with the planned harvest schedule.\", \"rainfall_forecast\": \"Precipitation: 0.0 mm, Mainly Clear\", \"spraying_advisory\": \"It is safe to spray pesticides/fungicides today, given the low wind speed and no forecasted rainfall.\", \"current_temperature\": \"30.7°C\", \"weather_recommendations\": [\"Recommendation 1: Increase irrigation frequency to compensate for high temperatures\", \"Recommendation 2: Consider using mulch or other methods to reduce soil temperature and retain moisture\"]}}','[{\"content\": \"Cotton (Gossypium hirsutum) bollworm management: Inspect weekly during boll formation. Use pheromone traps for monitoring. Apply Bt-based biopesticides at early instar stage. Recommended NPK: 120:60:60 kg/ha with micronutrients.\", \"metadata\": {\"crop\": \"Cotton\", \"source\": \"icar.org.in\", \"disease\": \"Bollworm\"}, \"relevance\": 1.3691}, {\"content\": \"General crop storage principles: Temperature and humidity control are critical. Most vegetables: 0–10°C, 85–95% RH. Grains: <15°C, <14% moisture. Fruits: 10–15°C, 85–90% RH. Use hermetic bags or cold rooms to extend shelf life.\", \"metadata\": {\"type\": \"storage\", \"source\": \"fao.org\"}, \"relevance\": 1.4569}, {\"content\": \"Integrated Pest Management (IPM) principles: 1. Cultural control: Crop rotation, resistant varieties, sanitation. 2. Biological control: Predatory insects, Bt, Trichoderma. 3. Chemical control: Last resort, use registered pesticides at correct dosage. 4. Monitoring: Regular scouting every 5–7 days.\", \"metadata\": {\"type\": \"ipm\", \"source\": \"fao.org\"}, \"relevance\": 1.46}, {\"content\": \"Tomato cultivation requires well-drained loamy soil with pH 6.0–7.0. Scientific name: Solanum lycopersicum. Growth duration: 60–90 days after transplanting. NPK recommendation: 120:60:60 kg/ha. Requires staking for indeterminate varieties.\", \"metadata\": {\"crop\": \"Tomato\", \"type\": \"overview\", \"source\": \"icar.org.in\"}, \"relevance\": 1.4829}]',18.506086,73.762144,37.17,'completed','','2026-06-18 11:25:01.701008','2026-06-18 11:25:38.879065'),(95,'crop_images/1ffeb88cdf7c4d15b64ecd1483252779.jpg','Sugarcane','Healthy',90,'[]','Healthy',97,'Low','{\"soil\": \"Well-drained loamy soil, pH 6.0-7.0, with adequate organic matter\", \"family\": \"Poaceae\", \"origin\": \"Southeast Asia\", \"climate\": \"Warm tropical, 20-30°C, with high humidity\", \"crop_name\": \"Sugarcane\", \"description\": \"Sugarcane is a highly important crop for sugar production, with a global production of over 1.8 billion tons per year. It is typically cultivated in tropical and subtropical regions using a variety of practices, including monoculture and intercropping. Sugarcane is a significant source of income for many farmers and contributes to the global sugar supply. Its cultivation requires careful management of soil, water, and pests to ensure optimal yields and sugar content.\", \"growth_duration\": \"12-18 months from planting\", \"scientific_name\": \"Saccharum officinarum\", \"water_requirement\": \"High, 800-1000 mm per season\"}','{\"causes\": [\"Optimal growing conditions, including adequate water, nutrients, and temperature\", \"Well-draining soil and proper aeration\", \"Regular pest and disease management practices\"], \"pathogen\": \"None\", \"symptoms\": [\"Normal green color and firm texture of Sugarcane stalks\", \"Absence of visible lesions, discoloration, or other signs of disease\", \"Presence of a strong, sweet scent from the Sugarcane\", \"Normal growth rate and vigor of Sugarcane plants\"], \"treatment\": [], \"prevention\": [\"Maintain optimal growing conditions, including adequate water, nutrients, and temperature\", \"Monitor soil moisture and adjust irrigation schedules as needed\", \"Implement integrated pest management (IPM) practices to prevent disease\"], \"precautions\": [\"No specific safety precautions are necessary for Healthy Sugarcane\", \"Wear protective clothing and eyewear when handling Sugarcane to prevent injury\"], \"disease_name\": \"Healthy\", \"affected_areas\": [\"leaf\", \"stem\", \"root\"], \"disease_progression\": \"Healthy Sugarcane does not progress or spread, as it is a normal state of the plant.\", \"recommended_actions\": [\"Continue to monitor Sugarcane plants for any signs of disease or stress\", \"Maintain regular crop management practices, including watering, fertilization, and pruning\", \"Consider conducting soil tests to ensure optimal nutrient levels\"]}','{\"packaging\": \"Perforated polyethylene bags or wooden crates lined with plastic sheeting\", \"shelf_life\": \"6-8 weeks\", \"storage_type\": \"Hermetic Bags or Silos with controlled ventilation\", \"humidity_range\": \"85-90% RH\", \"do_not_store_with\": \"Other sugarcane varieties, as cross-pollination can occur; also, avoid storing near strong-smelling crops, as sugarcane can absorb odors\", \"temperature_range\": \"10-13°C\", \"storage_conditions\": \"Well-ventilated storage area, avoid direct sunlight, maintain cleanliness and sanitation\", \"post_harvest_handling\": \"Pre-cooling to 10°C within 24 hours, grading and sorting to remove damaged stalks, washing to remove dirt and debris\", \"expected_spoilage_time\": \"2-3 weeks under poor conditions (high temperature and humidity)\"}','{\"dosage\": \"Total 300 kg/ha: Basal dose 150 kg/ha at transplanting, Top dressing 75 kg/ha at 20, 40, 60 DAT\", \"cautions\": \"Over-fertilization can lead to soil salinization, water pollution, and reduced soil fertility\", \"npk_ratio\": \"150:75:75 kg/ha\", \"micronutrients\": \"Zinc Sulphate 25 kg/ha, Boron 2 kg/ha, Manganese 10 kg/ha\", \"deficiency_signs\": \"Yellowing of leaves, stunted growth, reduced sugar content\", \"application_method\": \"Drip fertigation\", \"application_timing\": \"Basal dose at transplanting, Top dressing at 20, 40, 60 days after transplanting (DAT)\", \"organic_alternatives\": \"FYM (Farm Yard Manure) 25 t/ha, Vermicompost 10 t/ha\", \"recommended_fertilizer\": \"DAP (Diammonium Phosphate) + Urea\"}','{\"harvest_method\": \"Mechanical combine or manual hand-picking\", \"harvest_duration\": \"12-14 months from planting\", \"best_harvest_time\": \"Early morning when the dew is still present to minimize juice loss and improve quality\", \"equipment_required\": [\"Sugarcane harvester\", \"Juicer or crusher\", \"Tractor or other heavy machinery\"], \"harvest_indicators\": [\"Fruit color change to yellow or golden\", \"Brix reading of 18-20%\", \"Stem diameter of 2.5-3.5 cm\", \"Leaf senescence and drying\"], \"post_harvest_losses\": \"Typical post-harvest loss: 5-10% due to juice loss during transportation and storage; reduce by using airtight containers and minimizing transportation time\", \"pre_harvest_interval\": \"At least 21 days after the last pesticide application to ensure the juice is free from pesticide residues\", \"yield_considerations\": \"Average yield: 60-80 tons/ha under good conditions, 40-60 tons/ha under poor conditions\", \"expected_harvest_date\": \"February-March for Kharif, June-July for Rabi\"}','{\"current\": {\"rain_mm\": 0.0, \"condition\": \"Mainly Clear\", \"feels_like_c\": 31.2, \"temperature_c\": 30.9, \"wind_speed_kmh\": 19.0, \"humidity_percent\": 47, \"precipitation_mm\": 0.0, \"wind_direction_deg\": 275, \"cloud_cover_percent\": 27}, \"latitude\": 18.50618, \"timezone\": \"Asia/Kolkata\", \"longitude\": 73.761452, \"fetched_at\": \"2026-06-18T11:02:48.275033Z\", \"forecast_7_days\": [{\"date\": \"2026-06-18\", \"condition\": \"Light Drizzle\", \"temp_max_c\": 33.5,