nt disease spread and address any potential weather risks. By following the recommended actions and maintaining proper crop management practices, the farmer can ensure a healthy and productive crop.\", \"key_recommendations\": [\"Continue to follow IPM principles and monitor the crop regularly\", \"Maintain proper sanitation and hygiene practices to prevent disease spread\"]}, \"weather_analysis\": {\"humidity\": \"47%\", \"wind_speed\": \"18.7 km/h\", \"weather_risks\": [\"Risk of drought due to low rainfall\", \"Risk of wind damage to the crop\"], \"harvest_advisory\": \"The current weather forecast does not indicate a need to harvest early, but continue to monitor the crop and weather conditions\", \"rainfall_forecast\": \"Precipitation: 0.0 mm, Mainly Clear\", \"spraying_advisory\": \"It is safe to spray pesticides/fungicides today, but take necessary precautions to avoid drift and ensure proper coverage\", \"current_temperature\": \"30.7°C\", \"weather_recommendations\": [\"Irrigate the crop as needed to prevent water stress\", \"Take necessary precautions to protect the crop from wind damage\"]}}','[{\"content\": \"Integrated Pest Management (IPM) principles: 1. Cultural control: Crop rotation, resistant varieties, sanitation. 2. Biological control: Predatory insects, Bt, Trichoderma. 3. Chemical control: Last resort, use registered pesticides at correct dosage. 4. Monitoring: Regular scouting every 5–7 days.\", \"metadata\": {\"type\": \"ipm\", \"source\": \"fao.org\"}, \"relevance\": 1.3}, {\"content\": \"Maize (Zea mays) grey leaf spot disease. Symptoms: rectangular grey-brown lesions parallel to leaf veins. Management: Crop rotation, resistant hybrids, triazole fungicides. Maize NPK: 150:75:75 kg/ha. Harvest at 25–30% grain moisture.\", \"metadata\": {\"crop\": \"Maize\", \"source\": \"cgiar.org\", \"disease\": \"Grey Leaf Spot\"}, \"relevance\": 1.4436}, {\"content\": \"Cotton (Gossypium hirsutum) bollworm management: Inspect weekly during boll formation. Use pheromone traps for monitoring. Apply Bt-based biopesticides at early instar stage. Recommended NPK: 120:60:60 kg/ha with micronutrients.\", \"metadata\": {\"crop\": \"Cotton\", \"source\": \"icar.org.in\", \"disease\": \"Bollworm\"}, \"relevance\": 1.4949}, {\"content\": \"Banana Sigatoka disease (Mycosphaerella fijiensis) management: Remove and destroy infected leaves. Apply systemic fungicides (propiconazole). Maintain plant spacing for air circulation. Banana requires 13–15 months from planting to harvest. Storage: 13–14°C, 90–95% RH. Shelf life: 1–4 weeks.\", \"metadata\": {\"crop\": \"Banana\", \"source\": \"fao.org\", \"disease\": \"Sigatoka\"}, \"relevance\": 1.5235}]',18.506084,73.762169,28.16,'completed','','2026-06-18 11:39:21.112424','2026-06-18 11:39:49.280800'),(97,'crop_images/0ecc44e5560643419c593a9ff2cdf9e4.jpg','Sugarcane','Healthy',95,'[]','Healthy',97,'Low','{\"soil\": \"Well-drained loamy soil, pH 6.0-7.0, with adequate organic matter\", \"family\": \"Poaceae\", \"origin\": \"Southeast Asia\", \"climate\": \"Warm tropical, 20-30°C, with high humidity\", \"crop_name\": \"Sugarcane\", \"description\": \"Sugarcane is a highly important crop globally, providing sugar, biofuel, and animal feed. It is cultivated in tropical and subtropical regions, often using intensive irrigation and fertilization practices. Sugarcane cultivation requires careful management to control pests and diseases, such as the sugarcane borer and smut. The crop\'s economic value lies in its high sugar content and versatility in producing various products.\", \"growth_duration\": \"12-18 months from planting\", \"scientific_name\": \"Saccharum officinarum\", \"water_requirement\": \"High, 800-1200 mm per season\"}','{\"causes\": [\"Optimal growing conditions with adequate water, nutrients, and sunlight\", \"Well-draining soil and moderate temperatures between 20-30°C\", \"Proper crop management practices, including regular pruning and fertilization\"], \"pathogen\": \"None\